le":"1376–Afdød","1313–1378":"1313–1378","1317–1364":"1317–1364","1374":"1374","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1404":"1404","1348":"1348","1413":"1413","1336":"1336","1313":"1313","1412":"1412","1335":"1335","1378":"1378","1356":"1356","1411":"1411","1376":"1376","1364":"1364","about 1335":"omkring 1335","about 1376":"omkring 1376","about 1374":"omkring 1374","1317":"1317","Kinross-shire, Scotland":"Kinross-shire, Skotland","Scotland":"Skotland","Arnot, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1335–":"circa 1335–Overleden","1335–1411":"1335–1411","1335–Female":"1335–Overleden","1336–1356":"1336–1356","1336–Male":"1336–Overleden","1348–1412":"1348–1412","1330–1404":"1330–1404","1360–1413":"1360–1413","1374–Male":"1374–Overleden","1376–Male":"1376–Overleden","1313–1378":"1313–1378","1317–1364":"1317–1364","1374":"1374","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1404":"1404","1348":"1348","1413":"1413","1336":"1336","1313":"1313","1412":"1412","1335":"1335","1378":"1378","1356":"1356","1411":"1411","1376":"1376","1364":"1364","about 1335":"circa 1335","about 1376":"circa 1376","about 1374":"circa 1374","1317":"1317","Kinross-shire, Scotland":"Kinross-shire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","Arnot, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1335–":"about 1335–Deceased","1335–1411":"1335–1411","1335–Female":"1335–Deceased","1336–1356":"1336–1356","1336–Male":"1336–Deceased","1348–1412":"1348–1412","1330–1404":"1330–1404","1360–1413":"1360–1413","1374–Male":"1374–Deceased","1376–Male":"1376–Deceased","1313–1378":"1313–1378","1317–1364":"1317–1364","1374":"1374","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1404":"1404","1348":"1348","1413":"1413","1336":"1336","1313":"1313","1412":"1412","1335":"1335","1378":"1378","1356":"1356","1411":"1411","1376":"1376","1364":"1364","about 1335":"about 1335","about 1376":"about 1376","about 1374":"about 1374","1317":"1317","Kinross-shire, Scotland":"Kinross-shire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Arnot, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Oliphant","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (London) and Scottish (Fife): from Old French <i>olifard</i> or <i>olifant</i>, of uncertain meaning. It has been suggested that this might be a derivative of Old French <i>olif</i> ‘olive’ + the pejorative suffix <i>-ard</i> ‘derisive nickname for one who preferred an olive branch to more martial weapons’; it may have denoted a man twisted like an olive-tree. The variant <i>Olifant</i> may have resulted from the substitution in Old Norman French of the sequence <i>l-r</i> by <i>l-n</i>, leading to a false association with Old French <i>olifant</i> ‘elephant’. This heraldic beast appears in the Scottish family's coats of arms. Branches of the Anglo-Norman family owned lands in both England and Scotland. The surname is now chiefly Scottish.","English: possibly a topographic name from residence at an inn known as the <i>Olyphaunt</i> or ‘elephant’, though whether this gave rise to a hereditary surname is unknown."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Oliphant was born about 1335, in Scotland, her father, Walter Oliphant, was 24 and her mother, Elizabeth de Bruce, was 19. She had at least 3 sons with Sir Henry Arnot."},"et":{"about 1335–":"umbes 1335–Surnud","1335–1411":"1335–1411","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1336–1356":"1336–1356","1336–Male":"1336–Surnud","1348–1412":"1348–1412","1330–1404":"1330–1404","1360–1413":"1360–1413","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1313–1378":"1313–1378","1317–1364":"1317–1364","1374":"1374","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1